<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-450-046  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 450 046.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  July 1989 v6 n4 p29(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Start-Pat: a parallel-programming toolkit. (includes a relatedarticle on PCF Fortran) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Appelbe, Bill; Smith, Kevin; McDowell, Charlie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Start-Pat is a prototype integrated toolkit for the automaticparallelization of sequential FORTRAN code and the analysis of thesubsequent code for errors due to the parallelism process.andP;  Thereare a vast number of scientific and engineering applications andalgorithms written in sequential FORTRAN, but programmingmultitasking FORTRAN is a difficult and time-consuming task.andO;Consequently, a joint team from the Georgia Institute ofTechnology and the University of California (Santa Cruz) aredeveloping Start-Pat to help programmers convert sequentialFORTRAN to parallel environments and to learn application andarchitectural parallelism.andP;  Pat is the interactive parallelizer,while Start is a static analyzer.andP;  Both are written in C, supportFORTRAN-77 and Cray parallel tasking, use an X-Windows interface,and run on UNIX-based systems.andP;  Details of the components andfunctions of Start-Pat areandM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Program Development ToolsResearch and DevelopmentCode ConversionParallelismFORTRANParallel ProcessingUtility ProgramsMultitasking.andO;Feature:   illustrationprogramchart.andO;Caption:   A sequential Fortran source program. (program)Loop-carried dependencies. (chart)Asequential dependency graph generated by Pat. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>